{{Infobox NRHP | name =Colonel Crawford Burn Site Monument | nrhp_type = | image = Colonel Crawford Burn Site Monument drawing.jpg | caption = Artist's rendition of the monument | location = Northeast of [[Crawford, Ohio|Crawford]], [[Ohio]] | coordinates = {{coord|40|55|23|N|83|20|4|W|display=inline,title}} | locmapin = Ohio#USA | area = | built = 1877 | architect = John Wyandot | architecture= | added = April 15, 1982 | governing_body = Private | refnum=82003667<ref name="nris">{{NRISref|2008a}}</ref> }} [[File:Crawford Burn Site Monument.jpg|thumb|right|The [[Ohio Historical Society]]'s marker near the Colonel Crawford Burn Site]] [[File:Crawford Burn Site Monument (230th Anniversary Commemoration of the Battle of Sandusky).JPG|thumb|right|Crawford Burn Site Monument (230th Anniversary Commemoration of the Battle of Sandusky)]] [[Image:Crawford01.jpg|left|300px|thumb|Execution of Crawford]]
The '''Colonel Crawford Burn Site Monument''' is a war monument in rural [[Wyandot County, Ohio|Wyandot County]], [[Ohio]], [[United States]]. Placed in the 1870s, it commemorates the death by burning of Colonel [[William Crawford (soldier)|William Crawford]] during the concluding years of the American Revolution. The stone monument itself was long the subject of local interest, and it has been named a [[historic site]].
As the end of the [[American Revolutionary War|American Revolution]] approached, warfare continued in the backcountry of modern Ohio; British-allied Indians continued to harass the American settlers. In 1782, a regiment of [[Virginia]] soldiers was sent in reprisal to destroy Indian villages on the [[Sandusky River]], under the command of William Crawford, a friend of victorious General [[George Washington]]. However, the [[Crawford expedition]] ended on June 4 after a skirmish south of modern-day [[Carey, Ohio|Carey]], and the Americans retreated. Colonel Crawford [[Colonel Crawford Capture Site|was captured]] by the Indians after the battle, and seven days later he was tortured and [[burning at the stake|burned at the stake]] on the banks of Tymochtee Creek in present-day northeastern [[Wyandot County, Ohio|Wyandot County]].<ref>[http://www.remarkableohio.org/HistoricalMarker.aspx?historicalMarkerId=312 Colonel William Crawford/The 1782 Sandusky Campaign], [[Ohio Historical Society]], 1996. Accessed 2014-02-03.</ref>
As the centenary of the burning approached, a movement arose to commemorate Crawford's death with a monument. The movement's proponents were aroused by a strong sense of the incident's importance: besides being the earliest major event in Wyandot County history, it was the county's most prominent event of all time in their opinion. One of the county's leading lawyers, Curtis Berry, originated the idea of marking the site. The marker is made of [[sandstone]] from [[Berea, Ohio]], worked in the shape of a cannon and cut approximately {{convert|6.5|ft}} tall. Local labor at B.L. Bauscher's firm in [[Upper Sandusky, Ohio|Upper Sandusky]] performed the stone cutting during the middle of 1877, and the monument was dedicated later in the year. The dedication ceremony saw thousands of people in attendance.<ref>Owen, Lorrie K., ed. ''Dictionary of Ohio Historic Places''. Vol. 2. [[St. Clair Shores, Michigan|St. Clair Shores]]: Somerset, 1999, 1425.</ref> For many years, the local Pioneer Association hosted an annual Pioneer Picnic at the monument, until the deaths of older residents and the apathy of younger residents saw the demise of the event in 1935.<ref name=brown>Brown, Parker B. "[https://ojs.libraries.psu.edu/index.php/wph/article/viewFile/3928/3745 The Search for the Colonel William Crawford Burn Site: An Investigative Report]". ''The Western Pennsylvania Historical Magazine'' 68.1 (1985): 43-66.</ref>{{rp|43}} Interest returned in the 1970s: locals opposed the construction of a proposed electric transmission line by the site, and it became a popular location for school field trips.<ref name=brown />{{rp|45}}
In April 1982, the monument was listed on the [[National Register of Historic Places]], qualifying because of its connection to Crawford; it is one of [[National Register of Historic Places listings in Wyandot County, Ohio|ten such locations in Wyandot County]].<ref name=nris /> Commemorative monuments are typically ineligible for National Register listing, and sites such as the Crawford Burn Site Monument can qualify only if the markers themselves have become historically significant.<ref>[http://www.nps.gov/history/nr/publications/bulletins/nrb15/nrb15_2.htm National Register Criteria for Evaluation], [[National Park Service]]. Accessed 2010-02-03.</ref>
